  <static seed="1000" source="Contrib/PCC/BasicAlgebra/GraphingQuadratics/IdentifyAxisVertex110.pg">
    <statement><p>Find the axis of symmetry and vertex of the quadratic function.</p>
<p><m>{y}={4x^{2}-4x+2}</m></p>
<p>Axis of symmetry: <fillin characters="13" name="AnSwEr0001"/></p>
<p>Vertex: <fillin characters="13" name="AnSwEr0002"/></p>
</statement>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>x = 0.5</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <answer>
      <p>
        <m>\left(0.5,1\right)</m>
      </p>
    </answer>
    <solution><p>This quadratic function is given in standard form. Identify that:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{ a=4,b=-4,c=2 }</m></p>
<p>To find the parabola<rsq/>s axis of symmetry, we use the formula <m>\displaystyle{x=-\frac{b}{2a}}</m></p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
  x \amp = -\frac{b}{2a} \\
   \amp = -\frac{-4}{2(4)} \\
   \amp = 0.5
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>This parabola<rsq/>s axis of symmetry is <m>\displaystyle{x=0.5}</m>.</p>
<p>Next, substitute <m>\displaystyle{x=0.5}</m> into <m>\displaystyle{{y}={4x^{2}-4x+2}}</m>, we have:</p>
<p><m>\displaystyle{\begin{aligned}[t]
   y \amp = 4(0.5)^{2} - 4(0.5)+2 \\
    \amp = 4 \cdot 0.25 -2 + 2 \\
    \amp = {1}
\end{aligned}
    }</m></p>
<p>This parabola<rsq/>s vertex is <m>\displaystyle{(0.5,{1})}</m>.</p>
</solution>
